129	// ------------------------------------------------------------------
130	// TMA bulk-copy commit / wait wrappers
131	// ------------------------------------------------------------------
132	// ``cp.async.bulk.commit_group`` / ``cp.async.bulk.wait_group`` are the
133	// TMA-specific counterparts of the cp.async commit/wait primitives in
134	// ``ffpa::cp_async``. They track ONLY ``cp.async.bulk{,.tensor}`` copies
135	// and are independent of ``cp.async.commit_group`` (the legacy cp.async
136	// group counter does NOT track TMA, and vice versa).
137	//
138	// The SM90 K/V data path uses mbarrier-based completion (every TMA copy in
139	// ``load_2d`` arrives on its per-stage mbarrier via
140	// ``cuda::device::barrier_arrive_tx`` and is awaited in the kernel via
141	// ``wait_barrier_parity``). Mbarrier-tracking is strictly more
142	// expressive than the bulk-group counter (per-slot phases, no FIFO
143	// constraint), so the kernel does not currently call ``bulk_commit_group``
144	// / ``bulk_wait_group``. They are exposed here for two reasons:
145	//
146	//   1. Code-review clarity: it makes the cp.async vs TMA wait split
147	//      explicit. ``ffpa::cp_async::commit_group/wait_group`` only sync Q
148	//      (which is still on cp.async); K/V are synced via
149	//      ``consume_X_tile`` -> ``wait_barrier_parity``.
150	//   2. Future use: a fused bulk_wait_group<0> at the very end of the
151	//      kernel would let us drop the per-slot mbarrier waits if we later
152	//      decide to coarsen the schedule.
